Troubleshooting methodology.

Here's a truth about system administration: your real value isn't in having memorized a thousand commands. It's in having a flow, a quick mental checklist that turns a vague "something's broken" into a specific, actionable diagnosis. Panic makes people flail; a method keeps you moving. And nearly every problem fits the same six steps.

Step one, reproduce. If you can't reproduce the problem, you can't ever confirm you've fixed it. So find the trigger, the exact action or condition that makes it happen. Step two, narrow it down by asking what changed. A recent deploy? A new package? A reboot? The best single opener here is journalctl dash-dash-since "one hour ago" dash-p err, which shows you every error logged in the last hour. Step three, layer down. Start at the highest level of abstraction the user actually sees, and work downward: the application's own logs, then the service status with systemctl status, then the system journal, and finally the kernel ring buffer with dmesg.

Step four, bisect time. Ask, when did it last work? Tools like last, journalctl dash-b dash-one for the previous boot, and your package manager's history let you find the moment things changed. Step five, isolate your variables, meaning test just one factor at a time. If a service won't start, try running its binary by hand with the same environment. If you can't reach a host, ping its IP address directly, which bypasses DNS and tells you whether the problem is naming or connectivity. And step six, fix, then prevent. Patch the immediate symptom to stop the bleeding, then patch the underlying cause, and then, ideally, add monitoring so that next time you see it before your users do.

If you notice the thread running through all six steps, it's isolation. At every stage you're cutting the problem space in half. Is this the application or the system? This host or the network? DNS or the route? A config error or a permissions error? Every answer eliminates half of what it could be. The next five sections turn this instinct into muscle memory, with concrete playbooks for the five emergencies you'll meet most. Memorize the first command of each one, because that first command is what turns panic into procedure.
